es -- t25 The Abyss -- t26 Navigating the Curve -- t27 Tidy Columns -- tVI I AM THE CAPTAIN OF MY SHIP -- tIntroduction -- t28 Broader Impacts -- t29 Doo hwił hóyéeda . . . A Lesson Lost in Translation . . . -- t30 The Ridge -- t31 Who I Am -- t32 The Best Place for My Hearing Aids Is on My Desk -- tConclusion: Aid to Navigation -- tAcknowledgments -- tReflection and Discussion Questions -- tFurther Reading and Resources -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeople with disabilities are underrepresented in STEM fields, and all too often, they face isolation and ableism in academia. Uncharted is a collection of powerful first-person stories by current and former scientists with disabilities or chronic conditions who have faced changes in their careers, including both successes and challenges, because of their health. It gives voice to common experiences that are frequently overlooked or left unspoken. These deeply personal accounts describe not only health challenges but also the joys, sorrows, humor, and wonder of science and scientists.With a breadth of perspectives on being disabled or chronically ill, these stories highlight the intersectionality of minoritized identities with the disability community. Uncharted features essays by contributors who are d/Deaf, blind, neurodivergent, wheelchair users, have experienced traumatic brain injuries, have blood sugar disorders, have rare medical diagnoses, or have received psychiatric diagnoses, among many others. In many cases, the scientific field is not fully accessible to them, and they frankly describe struggling as well as thriving alongside their conditions.This book serves as representation for scientists who have never felt comfortable disclosing their disability or who have never felt fully understood. The stories shared in this book seek to normalize medical conditions and disabilities in scientific culture, offering recommendations for how and why to improve access. Uncharted is vital and compelling reading for current and aspiring scientists who want to make their fields more inclusive and supportive for everyone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSciencexVocational guidance. 0aScientists with disabilitiescAnecdotes. 0aScientists with disabilitiesvAnecdotes. 0aScientistsxHealth and hygienevAnecdotes. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aAsani, Furaha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayer, Skylar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Sami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett, Glyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFern, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancisco, Taylor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarazin, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayden, Maureen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeidt, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKgoadi, Mpho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarks, Gabriela Serrato, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMartin, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenezes, Sunshine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNolan, Syreeta L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct